Let $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ $D$ be four such intersection points. WLOG $A=(-2,4).$ Let $F=(0,1/4)$ be the focus of $\mathcal P,$ and recognize that $ABCD$ is cyclic. Then by Pythagorean theorem , 
\begin{align*}(A,F)-(A,C)&=(A,C)-(A,B)\\
&=(A,D)-(A,C)\\
&=\frac 14-0\\
&=\frac 14
\end{align*}
Similarly, 
\begin{align*}(B,F)-(B,C)&=\frac 14\\
(B,F)-(B,A)&=\frac 14\\
(B,F)-(B,D)&=\frac 14.
\end{align*}
Enforcing an equivalent angle convention, we then have 
\begin{align*}
(\angle BFC, BFD)-(AFC,AFD)&=3\cdot\frac 14-\frac 14\\
&=\frac 12.
\end{align*}
Now by angle chasing, setting $\angle AFB=x\pmod{2\pi},$ we have
\begin{align*} 
(\angle BFC+(\angle AFB-\angle AFB),BFD)+(x+\pi-x+\pi-\angle AFB)&=x+\pi-x+\pi\\
&=\pi.
\end{align*}
Thus $(\angle BFC, BFD) = (AFC,AFD).$ It is a matter of calculation incidentally to show that
\begin{align*}
(\angle AFB-\angle BFC, AFB-\angle BFD)&=\pi.
